		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I don't think (personally) the reason they gave Hayabusa as is name is to make it more distinguishable. Usually in japan, you always call people by their familly name, never from their first name. The only rare case is when you're very very close with that person. </div>
<br />It's weird because according to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Family_name" class="postlink">wikipedia</a> Japan was one of the late countries to addopt the usage of family names.
<br />
<br />Also, it's quite common here to call people by their family name. Typically someone is called by his first name inside the family, because everyone have the same family name obviously, and by the family name at work/scool because it's likely someone else have the same surname, but not likely someone else have the same family name. Someone with a surname which isn't too comon could be called by both unpreferably.
<br />
<br />I think it has nothing to do with how close you are. For example consider someone named John Smith, John being his first name and Smith his family name. Then it would probably sound more polite/distant to call him "Mr. John" than to call him plain "Smith".
<br />
<br />I don't have played the Genesis (Genesis is american name for Megadrive right ? This always remember me the rock group) version of BROJ, but I don't want to if it's really horrible. All Megadrive/Genesis music sound horrible anyway from what I've heard. I really can't like FM synthetis.
<br />
<br />And yes, Celius&amp;Tokumaru, I hope your Castlevania/Sonic games respecively will be as great as you hope so. I hope you're not having too much trouble to code objects/enemies as I do with my game engine.

		

