		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Yes if this was a beat-em up game I remember it had a nice techno track that used well the FM hardware (if it's not then I'm confusing it). But then FM is limited to techno only or bad song, which is more limited than sampling which allow both for classical or modern oriented music.<br />PSG like on the NES also allow both classical-like music (Dragon Quest) or rock-like music (Battletoads).</div>
<br />
<br />Sounds the same as what I think, as a writer of horrendous songs on every general type of sound system, that with sampling (and FM if you're playful enough with the chip) it's really easy to write bad music but still make it sound good (good instrument use).  It's also not hard to find great music that sounds bad (poor instrument use).
<br />
<br />There's equal art and science to chipmusic.  PSG just gives you this clear and distinctive sound, FM and samples both can get really muddied (by design, often).

		

